Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 46th Weekly Dose of Optimism. This see=
ms like one of those weeks that we=E2=80=99ll look back on in a few years. =
So much big, potentially world-changing stuff happening all at once.
This is going to be packed edition.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1//spon) The Weekly Dose is brought to you by... Pirate Wires [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/6e41a502-ec22-4aaf-b3e7-7704a8dad9b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
There=E2=80=99s so much to be optimistic about this week that even our spon=
sor is guesting with a brief, morning white pill. Mike Solana [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/ec81e0aa-e89f-4063-8ca6-5a40addc83ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] runs Pirate Wires [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/6e41a502-ec22-4aaf-b3e7-7704a8dad9b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], an independent med=
ia company reporting at the intersection of technology, politics, and cultu=
re. He and his team publish multiple news roundups a week on the evolving i=
nformation landscape, mind-bending new developments in tech, media distorti=
on, government regulation, and, occasionally, that good Twitter drama. They=
 also publish feature-length bangers from both staff and guest writers, esp=
ousing a flavor of =E2=80=9Cbased optimism=E2=80=9D that we dig here at Not=
 Boring. Take the mic, Mike:
Last week, a clip featuring what appears to be one of the UAE=E2=80=99s suc=
cessful inductions of desert rain [ https://substack.com/redirect/206bd003-=
dce3-459e-b8f4-0baa4c908796?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] went viral, sparking a wild conversation on the topic=
 of geoengineering, including a good helping of my favorite kind of hater: =
mad because a thing is =E2=80=98fake,=E2=80=99 but also if it isn=E2=80=99t=
 fake it=E2=80=99s bad. The anti-tech camp tends to bring together two unli=
kely tribes, FernGully environmentalists who believe =E2=80=9Cnature=E2=80=
=9D is perfect just the way it is, and Republicans who don=E2=80=99t want t=
o spend any money. The impulse from both camps is to just do nothing, and e=
ventually die. I do not share this impulse.
The concept of man-made global warming poses an interesting corollary to th=
e premise we=E2=80=99ve screwed up our environment: if we can change our pl=
anet at all, can=E2=80=99t we also change it for the better? The answer is =
obviously yes =E2=80=94=C2=A0and we should.
It=E2=80=99s 2023, we need to be terraforming Earth.
Hygroscopic cloud seeding has existed for decades, including throughout the=
 United States [ https://substack.com/redirect/f31219c2-7635-4897-abcd-6402=
121fa758?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]. We have more than enough evidence to justify further resources in the f=
ield for research and development. Too much carbon in the atmosphere, and a=
 devastated global fish supply? Turns out dumping iron in the ocean=E2=80=
=99s barren groves [ https://substack.com/redirect/26ec9d16-a96c-45ca-92df-=
7803fd026f54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] solves both of these problems. Deserts? Should not exist. California=
=E2=80=99s Salton Sea [ https://substack.com/redirect/c80ffd16-97bd-49f8-8f=
d9-4f58b1c7f24b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], which is currently dying because it hasn=E2=80=99t been replenis=
hed, was our accidental test-case. Next up? We=E2=80=99re seaflooding [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/5722188c-003a-4cf1-82a2-6b829ea4b1f4?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] the Sahara, lower=
ing the global sea level, and turning Northern Africa into a breadbasket (a=
gain [ https://substack.com/redirect/7a912b83-d5b4-43ea-98cb-447a4b3decd8?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]).
Earth is a garden. Our garden, in fact. It=E2=80=99s time to weed the garde=
n.
That's just a little taste. Pirate Wires [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e=
41a502-ec22-4aaf-b3e7-7704a8dad9b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is one of our favorites and you should definit=
ely subscribe for more.
(2) Introducing Apple Vision Pro
Packy here. Taking over for Dan because I have some thoughts.=20
Everything about the Apple Vision Pro announcement is why we get out of bed=
 over here at Not Boring. Obviously, the tech is cool and I=E2=80=99m excit=
ed to try it, but that=E2=80=99s not what I=E2=80=99m talking about. I=E2=
=80=99m talking about the reactions.=20
AR/VR is one of the canonical overhyped technologies, something people have=
 pointed to when talking about the fact that some technologies just get too=
 overhyped and never recover. There have been countless tweets and articles=
 about why AR/VR wasn=E2=80=99t going to happen, and countless more about t=
he death of the =E2=80=9Cmetaverse=E2=80=9D and the foolishness of anyone w=
ho got excited about it in the first place. There are infinity such article=
s, but for some reason, the one that sticks in my mind is the two-part piec=
e from The Information in May 2022: The Inside Story of Why Apple Bet Big o=
n a Mixed-Reality Headset [ https://substack.com/redirect/25ce24b9-4c50-490=
2-ab18-3f22d8225717?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
There wasn=E2=80=99t anything particularly wrong about the article. In fact=
, the reporting was quite good, with a lot of intel from inside the normall=
y secretive company. It even nailed that the device would look like ski gog=
gles. But there was also the usual stuff: cost overruns, delays, a rumor th=
at Tim Cook didn=E2=80=99t give the headset project the same attention Stev=
e Jobs had given the iPhone and the fretting about what all of that might m=
ean for the project=E2=80=99s chances.=20
I remember reading it on my phone in my kitchen and thinking that none of t=
he stuff in there would matter when Apple finally released the headset beca=
use it would be beautiful and shiny and everyone would want to buy one and =
people would start getting really excited about AR or VR or MR or XR or whi=
chever Reality Apple chose to present to us=E2=80=A6 and on Monday, that=E2=
=80=99s exactly what happened.=20
Apple announced the Vision Pro on Monday, and the reviews, particularly fro=
m those who got the chance to demo the device, have been glowing. AR is now=
 the New Thing.=20
This is what bugs me so much about techno-pessimism. There=E2=80=99s no con=
viction.=20
If all it takes to change your mind is one predictably stunning Apple prese=
ntation=E2=80=A6
=E2=80=A6which is totally fine, just next time, take a beat and think, =E2=
=80=9CWhat would I think about X if Apple put its might behind making one?=
=E2=80=9D before dunking. =20
The Vision Pro situation captures the general problem nicely.=20
People are able to touch and feel the current, shitty stepping stone versio=
n of any product. They=E2=80=99re able to easily point out its flaws and op=
ine on how something like that could never work. But, like, of course. It=
=E2=80=99s a shitty stepping stone version.=20
It=E2=80=99s much harder to imagine what the best people in the world will =
build when given the time, resources, iterations, and lessons to do it bett=
er than anyone has ever done it. If you could, you=E2=80=99d be one of the =
best people in the world, and you=E2=80=99d be building it.=20
Anyway, now we=E2=80=99re going to enter a period of AR/VR/MR/Metaverse (or=
, sorry, Spatial) hype and people are going to start creating all sorts of =
apps for the Vision Pro, some as silly as iBeer [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/d00a6557-156a-4f3b-922f-bebe16e6e000?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and I Am Rich [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/be6df543-2ab6-4602-9f8c-5bf6d13833c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and some of them will be kind of coo=
l and a bunch of them won=E2=80=99t work and then other people are going to=
 learn from them and keep experimenting and iterating and tweaking, and the=
n we=E2=80=99ll get the Ubers and Airbnbs and WhatsApps of Spatial and it w=
ill all seem very obvious in hindsight, like mobile.=20
Or like AI, biotech, electric cars, space, solar, the list goes on [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/db882c40-5f80-4d4e-8d42-25ee4cbd7c81?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The Gartner Hype Cy=
cle remains undefeated.=20
Any sufficiently valuable technology will attract swarms [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/07ac618b-3278-4e76-ad7=
0-e6986e734643?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of talent and capital, will go=
 through bubbles and pops, until all of the little things that go into gett=
ing it right snap into place, the economics start making sense, and someone=
 figures out a good way to make it happen. It=E2=80=99s practically a law o=
f technology physics.=20
Here=E2=80=99s to the crazy ones, the optimists who=E2=80=99ve had convicti=
on around AR and VR and xR and virtual worlds before Apple showed everyone =
else that they were probably right all along.=20
(3) The Unintended Consequences of Censoring Digital Technology =E2=80=93 E=
vidence from Italy=E2=80=99s ChatGPT Ban [ https://substack.com/redirect/e5=
7c0128-e03b-448b-a0d4-daddad4237ab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Research from David Kreitmeir and Paul A. Raschky
We analyse the effects of the ban of ChatGPT, a generative pre-trained tran=
sformer chatbot, on individual productivity. We first compile data on the h=
ourly coding output of over 8,000 professional GitHub users in Italy and ot=
her European countries to analyse the impact of the ban on individual produ=
ctivity. Combining the high-frequency data with the sudden announcement of =
the ban in a difference-in-differences framework, we find that the output o=
f Italian developers decreased by around 50% in the first two business days=
 after the ban and recovered after that.
A new study found that developer output decreased by 50% when ChatGPT was b=
anned in Italy. Of course, developers being the resourceful folks that they=
 are, found ways around the ban and output rebounded in just two days.=20
However, the abrupt ban and subsequent drop in productivity paints a pretty=
 clear picture as to how useful ChatGPT is for developers. Let=E2=80=99s as=
sume that pre-ChatGPT developers were at a 1x output and the introduction o=
f ChatGPT raised developer output to (conservatively) 1.25x. What will deve=
loper output look like when:=20
ChatGPT is much more powerful
An ecosystem of ChatGPT-native developer tools are released
Developers are schooled and trained to use ChatGPT as part of their workflo=
ws
I think it=E2=80=99s fair to say that developer output guess 2-3x over the =
coming years (disclosure: I=E2=80=99m not a developer), which will have maj=
or implications on company building and should also result in an abundance =
of new technologies.
(4) Taurine deficiency as a driver of aging [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/8307ca18-5272-4be0-afe4-c790b3b03f3e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Singh et al for Science
Supplementation with taurine slowed key markers of aging such as increased =
DNA damage, telomerase deficiency, impaired mitochondrial function, and cel=
lular senescence. Loss of taurine in humans was associated with aging-relat=
ed diseases, and concentrations of taurine and its metabolites increased in=
 response to exercise. Taurine supplementation improved life span in mice a=
nd health span in monkeys.
A new study published in Science found that the dietary supplement taurine =
"delayed death" and mitigated against the biological risks of aging in mice=
 populations. Taurine, a popular supplement among the bodybuilder crowd, is=
 naturally found in various foods and often time added to energy drinks. Th=
e study also found improvements in strength, memory, and metabolism. Most s=
urprisingly, middle-aged mice that regularly took taurine lived significant=
ly longer than those that did not.
Hey, are you guys thinking what I'm thinking...? Looks like Create [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/5a656737-7673-4674-98d0-5e2bb3d95c55?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] just found its secon=
d product line.
(5) Why AI Will Save the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/a942bb99-ad2=
d-489a-96d8-d40560e0687d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Marc Andreesen for Andreesen Horowitz
A shorter description of what AI isn=E2=80=99t: Killer software and robots =
that will spring to life and decide to murder the human race or otherwise r=
uin everything, like you see in the movies [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
f3eee3c3-f27f-4a12-b558-cb85bfd54c14?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
An even shorter description of what AI could be: A way to make everything w=
e care about better.
Every couple of years, Marc Andreessen drops an essay that ignites a moveme=
nt and unleashes a flood of resources. A few notable examples are:
"Why Software Is Eating the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/b488969c-=
bd93-43b7-aa9d-b119d60ad635?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]" (2011)
"It's Time to Build [ https://substack.com/redirect/a30e31a9-4070-4bf2-a388=
-6ddf8a83c0e1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]" (2020)
This most recent essay, published this week, is his optimistic argument for=
 =E2=80=9CWhy AI Will Save the World.=E2=80=9D To make this argument, he of=
 course had to address the counter argument: why AI is going to kill us all=
 and ruin society. In his view, it=E2=80=99s a pretty simple one to debunk:
AI doesn=E2=80=99t want, it doesn=E2=80=99t have goals, it doesn=E2=80=99t =
want to kill you, because it=E2=80=99s not alive.
=E2=80=9CAI Alignment=E2=80=9D is a form of thought-policing.
Technology waves have always created new jobs.
Say what you will about these arguments =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s really hard =
to prove that something won=E2=80=99t happen. Andreessen doesn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve a crystal ball. but he does have about as deep of an understanding of te=
chnology history as anyone to inform his projections.
Counterarguments aside, what I find more compelling is why he thinks =E2=80=
=9CAI Will Save the World.=E2=80=9D This argument centers on intelligence, =
and AI=E2=80=99s ability to augment human intelligence.
Human intelligence is the lever that we have used for millennia to create t=
he world we live in today: science, technology, math, physics, chemistry, m=
edicine, energy, construction, transportation, communication, art, music, c=
ulture, philosophy, ethics, morality. Without the application of intelligen=
ce on all these domains, we would all still be living in mud huts, scratchi=
ng out a meager existence of subsistence farming. Instead we have used our =
intelligence to raise our standard of living on the order of 10,000X over t=
he last 4,000 years.
According to Andreessen, what AI offers is the opportunity to profoundly au=
gment human intelligence to make all of these outcomes of intelligence much=
, much better. The results?
Every child will have a personalized tutor
Every person will have an AI coach, advisor, and mentor
Every scientist, researcher, artist, inventor will have an AI assistant tha=
t allows them to increase the scope and depth of their work
World leaders and CEO will be aided in policy and decision making
Simply put: anything that people do with human intelligence can be done muc=
h better with AI assistance. AI makes human intelligence more intelligent. =
And elevated human intelligence is what has always driven civilization forw=
ard. This is the optimistic, abundance-focused view of the world that we su=
bscribe to at Not Boring.=20
IT=E2=80=99S TIME TO AI.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Mo=
nday. Enjoy the weekend!
Thanks for reading,
-Dan +Packy

